 "stories": [
  {
   "title": "A river sent through a mountain",
   "text": "At Milton, NID skims the Middle Yuba into a 22,600-ft tunnel bored through the divide into Bowman Lake. USGS gauges show the tunnel taking ~96% of the river's July\u2013September flow \u2014 94\u2013139 cfs into the mountain, 4\u20136 cfs left in the riverbed.",
   "anchor": [
    -120.5985,
    39.4955
   ],
   "box": [
    -120.502,
    39.688
   ],
   "width": 11.0
  },
  {
   "title": "Grand Central, elevation 5,014 ft",
   "text": "Nearly every drop of two FERC projects funnels through Lake Spaulding, then splits three ways: up to 840 cfs west into the Drum Canal toward the Bear River, 146 cfs to Nevada City down the 1850s South Yuba Canal \u2014 and just 16 cfs out the dam's river outlet.",
   "anchor": [
    -120.64287,
    39.32714
   ],
   "box": [
    -120.502,
    39.302
   ],
   "width": 11.0
  },
  {
   "title": "The two-tunnel relay",
   "text": "Our House Dam pushes the Middle Yuba through Lohman Ridge into Oregon Creek; 1,000 ft later Log Cabin Dam re-diverts everything through the Camptonville Tunnel into New Bullards Bar. In an average July, roughly half the Middle Yuba's flow ends up in the reservoir.",
   "anchor": [
    -121.02,
    39.428
   ],
   "box": [
    -121.245,
    39.668
   ],
   "width": 14.5
  },
  {
   "title": "One dam, two-thirds of the basin's storage",
   "text": "New Bullards Bar (1969) stores 966,103 af behind a 645-ft arch \u2014 water that drops 1,306 ft to spin New Colgate's 340-MW Pelton wheels, the largest ever cast. Its high spillway gates, an Oroville-style flaw, will be fixed by new gates 31.5 ft lower: the ARC spillway.",
   "anchor": [
    -121.1431,
    39.3933
   ],
   "box": [
    -121.395,
    39.475
   ],
   "width": 14.0
  },
  {
   "title": "Dams built for mud, not water",
   "text": "Hydraulic monitors washed ~680 million cubic yards of the Sierra into the Yuba \u2014 triple the Panama Canal's dig \u2014 burying farms and raising riverbeds. Daguerre Point (1906) and Englebright (1941) were built to trap that debris; Englebright still walls salmon out of the entire upper watershed.",
   "anchor": [
    -121.2694,
    39.24
   ],
   "box": [
    -121.658,
    39.125
   ],
   "width": 16.0
  },
  {
   "title": "A creek that runs on borrowed water",
   "text": "Deer Creek's own watershed yields little; its dependable flow is Yuba headwater imported through the South Yuba Canal. From Scotts Flat, NID meters ~53,000 af a year into 75 canals serving 25,000 connections \u2014 Gold Rush ditches still delivering the drinking water.",
   "anchor": [
    -120.93,
    39.268
   ],
   "box": [
    -121.06,
    39.118
   ],
   "width": 15.0
  },
  {
   "title": "February 2026 \u2014 the plumbing breaks",
   "text": "On Feb 13, 2026, New Colgate's 14-ft penstock ruptured, sending ~400 acre-feet down the hillside and knocking out the basin's biggest powerhouse. One pipe failure re-plumbed the river: flood releases shifted to the spillway and the lower Yuba's fish flows now lean on Englebright.",
   "anchor": [
    -121.1908,
    39.3307
   ],
   "box": [
    -121.545,
    39.302
   ],
   "width": 14.5
  }
 ],
